{"title_page": "Helen Sauls-August", "text_new": "{{short description|Speaker of the Eastern Cape Provincial Legislature}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                = Helen Sauls-August\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific-suffix    = [[Member of the Provincial Legislature|MPL]]\n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| smallimage          = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             =\n| office              = Speaker of the [[Eastern Cape Provincial Legislature]]\n| deputy              = Mlibo Qoboshiyane\n| term_start          = 22 May 2019\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Noxolo Kiviet]]\n| successor           = \n| birthname           = Helen Mercedes Sauls-August\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1968|07|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = \n| death_date          =  \n| death_place         = \n| citizenship         =\n| nationality         = [[South Africa]]n\n| party               = [[African National Congress]]\n| otherparty          = \n| spouse              = \n| partner             =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations           = \n| children            = \n| residence           = \n| education           = \n| alma_mater          = \n| occupation          = \n| profession          = \n| known_for           = \n| committees          = \n| portfolio           = Politician\n| awards              =  \n| website             = \n}}\n'''Helen Mercedes Sauls-August''' (born 24 July 1968) is a South African politician who serves as the Speaker of the [[Eastern Cape Provincial Legislature]], after having been elected on 22 May 2019. She previously served as the provincial MEC for Human Settlement and then the MEC for Health. She is a party member of the [[African National Congress]]. Sauls-August was peviously a councillor of the [[Nelson Mandela Metropolitan Municipality]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Eastern Cape to hold its first sitting for sixth administration |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eastern-cape-to-hold-its-first-sitting-for-sixth-administration-23724376 |accessdate=6 April 2020 |newspaper=IOL news |date=22 May 2019|location=Eastern Cape}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Helen Sauls-August ready for the Bhisho hot seat |url=https://www.heraldlive.co.za/weekend-post/your-weekend/2019-05-25-helen-sauls-august-ready-for-the-bhisho-hot-seat/ |accessdate=6 April 2020 |newspaper=HeraldLIVE |date=25 May 2019 |location=East London}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://www.pa.org.za/person/helen-sauls-august/ Helen Mercedes Sauls-August \u2013 People's Assembly]\n{{SouthAfrica-politician-stub}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sauls-August, Helen}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Members of the Eastern Cape Provincial Legislature]]\n[[Category:People from the Eastern Cape]]\n[[Category:African National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of provincial legislatures of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Women legislative speakers]]\n[[Category:South African women in politics]]\n[[Category:South African politicians]]\n[[Category:Politicians from the Eastern Cape]]\n[[Category:Coloured South African people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Speaker of the Eastern Cape Provincial Legislature}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| name                = Helen Sauls-August\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific-suffix    = [[Member of the Provincial Legislature|MPL]]\n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| smallimage          = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n| alt                 = \n| caption             =\n| office              = Speaker of the [[Eastern Cape Provincial Legislature]]\n| deputy              = Mlibo Qoboshiyane\n| term_start          = 22 May 2019\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Noxolo Kiviet]]\n| successor           = \n| birthname           = Helen Mercedes Sauls-August\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1968|07|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = \n| death_date          =  \n| death_place         = \n| citizenship         =\n| nationality         = [[South Africa]]n\n| party               = [[African National Congress]]\n| otherparty          = \n| spouse              = \n| partner             =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n| relations           = \n| children            = \n| residence           = \n| education           = \n| alma_mater          = \n| occupation          = \n| profession          = \n| known_for           = \n| committees          = \n| portfolio           = Politician\n| awards              =  \n| website             = \n}}\n'''Helen Mercedes Sauls-August''' (born 24 July 1968) is a South African politician who serves as the Speaker of the [[Eastern Cape Provincial Legislature]], after having been elected on 22 May 2019. She previously served as the provincial MEC for Human Settlement and then the MEC for Health. She is a party member of the [[African National Congress]]. Sauls-August was peviously a councillor of the [[Nelson Mandela Metropolitan Municipality]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Eastern Cape to hold its first sitting for sixth administration |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/eastern-cape-to-hold-its-first-sitting-for-sixth-administration-23724376 |accessdate=6 April 2020 |newspaper=IOL news |date=22 May 2019|location=Eastern Cape}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Helen Sauls-August ready for the Bhisho hot seat |url=https://www.heraldlive.co.za/weekend-post/your-weekend/2019-05-25-helen-sauls-august-ready-for-the-bhisho-hot-seat/ |accessdate=6 April 2020 |newspaper=HeraldLIVE |date=25 May 2019 |location=East London}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[https://www.pa.org.za/person/helen-sauls-august/ Helen Mercedes Sauls-August \u2013 People's Assembly]\n{{SouthAfrica-politician-stub}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sauls-August, Helen}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Members of the Eastern Cape Provincial Legislature]]\n[[Category:People from the Eastern Cape]]\n[[Category:African National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of provincial legislatures of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Women legislative speakers]]\n[[Category:South African women in politics]]\n[[Category:South African politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Lefcentreright", "label": "safe", "comment": "+Category:Politicians from the Eastern Cape; +Category:Coloured South African peopleusingHotCatAdded 2 categories", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helen_Sauls-August"}
{"title_page": "Ava DuVernay", "text_new": "{{short description|American film director}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Ava DuVernay\n| image = Ava DuVernay 2015.jpg\n| alt = Ava DuVernay in 2015.\n| caption = DuVernay in 2015\n| birth_name = Ava Marie DuVernay\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1972|08|24}}\n| birth_place = [[Long Beach, California]], U.S.\n| nationality = American \n| Education = [[Saint Joseph High School]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of California,&nbsp;Los Angeles]]\n| occupation = Filmmaker\n| notable_works = {{Unbulleted list|[[Selma (film)|''Selma'']]|''[[13th (film)|13th]]''|''[[A Wrinkle in Time (2018 film)|A Wrinkle in Time]]''|''[[When They See Us]]''}}\n| website = {{url|www.avaduvernay.com|AvaDuVernay.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Ava Marie DuVernay''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|dj|u\u02d0|v|\u025b\u0259r|\u02c8|n|e\u026a}}; born August 24, 1972) is an American filmmaker and film distributor. She won the directing award in the U.S. dramatic competition at the [[2012 Sundance Film Festival]] for her second feature film ''[[Middle of Nowhere (2012 film)|Middle of Nowhere]]'',<ref name=HuffPo-MoN-2012>{{cite news|first1=Gene|last1=Demby|title=Sundance 2012: Ava DuVernay Becomes First Black Woman To Win Best Director Prize For ''Middle Of Nowhere''|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/01/30/ava-duvernay-sundance_n_1241286.html|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=January 30, 2012}}</ref> becoming the first black woman to win the award.<ref name=LATimes-MoN-2012>{{cite news|first1=Mindy|last1=Farabee|title=Ava DuVernay no longer in 'Middle of Nowhere'|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2012/dec/20/entertainment/la-et-mn-middle-of-nowhere-ava-duvernay-20121220|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=December 20, 2012}}</ref> For her work on ''[[Selma (film)|Selma]]'' (2014), DuVernay became the first black woman to be nominated for a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Director]], and also the first black female director to have her film nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Picture]].<ref name=HReporter-SelmaGG-2014>{{cite news|last1=Ford|first1=Rebecca|title=Golden Globes: 'Selma's' Ava DuVernay Becomes First Black Woman to Receive Director Nomination|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/golden-globes-selmas-ava-duvernay-756511|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=December 11, 2014}}</ref><ref name=Guardian-Selma-2014>{{cite news|last1=Suskind|first1=Alex|title=How Ava DuVernay struck a chord with Selma|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/dec/17/ava-duvernay-film-director-selma|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=December 17, 2014}}</ref> In 2017, she was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature]] for her film ''[[13th (film)|13th]]'' (2016).\n\nDuVernay's 2018 Disney children's fantasy film ''[[A Wrinkle in Time (2018 film)|A Wrinkle in Time]]'' made her the first black woman to direct a live-action film earning $100 million at U.S. box office.<ref name=LATimes-WrinkleBudget-2016>{{cite news|last1=Keegan|first1=Rebecca|title=With 'A Wrinkle In Time,' Ava DuVernay will pass a milestone|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-wrinkle-budget-20160803-snap-story.html|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=August 3, 2016}}</ref> \n\nThe following year, she created, co-wrote, produced and directed the [[Netflix]] drama limited series ''[[When They See Us]]'', based on the 1989 [[Central Park jogger case]], which has earned critical acclaim.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/tv/news/netflix-and-ava-duvernay-win-dismissal-of-defamation-suit/ar-BB11BC9V|title=Netflix and Ava DuVernay Win Dismissal of Defamation Suit|website=www.msn.com|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref name=\"WhenTheySeeUsNetflixOrder\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gq.com/story/ava-duvernay-i-want-you-to-see-them|title=I Want You to See Them|last=Mayard|first=Judnick|work=[[GQ]]|date=May 30, 2019|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/when_they_see_us/s01|title=When They See Us: Season 1 (2019)|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|access-date=May 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/when-they-see-us|title=When They See Us|publisher=[[CBS]]|website=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=May 29, 2019}}</ref> The series was nominated for 16 Emmy Awards including the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Limited Series]] and won the [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Movie/Miniseries|Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Limited Series]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nDuVernay was born on August 24, 1972, in [[Long Beach, California]]. She was raised by her mother, Darlene ([[n\u00e9e]] Sexton), an educator, and her stepfather, Murray Maye.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.biography.com/people/ava-duvernay|title=Ava DuVernay|accessdate=September 22, 2016|date=May 24, 2016|work=Biography.com}}</ref> The surname of her biological father, Joseph Marcel DuVernay III, originates with [[Louisiana Creole]] ancestry.<ref name=fdr1>Stated on ''[[Finding Your Roots]]'', [[PBS]], October 24, 2017.</ref> She grew up in [[Lynwood, California]] (near [[Compton, California|Compton]]).<ref name=wrap15>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/ava-duvernay-reviews-straight-outta-compton-in-18-tweets-they-got-it-right/|title=Ava DuVernay Reviews 'Straight Outta Compton' in 18 Tweets: 'They Got It Right'|accessdate=September 22, 2016|last=Cunningham|first=Todd|date=August 16, 2015|publisher=[[TheWrap]]}}</ref> She has four brothers and sisters.\n\nDuring her summer vacations, she would travel to the childhood home of her father, which was not far from [[Selma, Alabama]].<ref name=60Minutes-Selma-2015>{{cite news|last1=Simon|first1=Bob|title=Where 'Selma' Meets Hollywood|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/selma-ava-duvernay-60-minutes/|work=[[60 Minutes]]|publisher=[[CBS News]]|date=February 8, 2015|format=TV interview/segment}}</ref> DuVernay said that these summers influenced the making of ''Selma,'' as her father had witnessed the 1965 [[Selma to Montgomery marches]].<ref name=RStone-Selma-2015>{{cite news|last1=Edwards|first1=Gavin|title=We Shall Overcome: Ava DuVernay on Making 'Selma'|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/features/ava-duvernay-on-making-selma-20150105|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=January 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990, DuVernay graduated from [[St. Joseph High School (Lakewood, California)|Saint Joseph High School]] in [[Lakewood, California|Lakewood]].<ref name=StJosephsHighSchool-2015>{{cite web|title=SJ Alumna Receives A Golden Globe Nomination|url=https://www.sj-jester.org/apps/news/article/425495|work=[[St. Joseph High School (Lakewood, California)|St. Joseph's High School]]|access-date=January 13, 2015}}</ref> At the [[University of California, Los Angeles]] (UCLA), she was a double BA major in [[English literature]] and [[African-American studies]]. Ava is an honorary member of [[Alpha Kappa Alpha]] sorority. <ref name=Biography-Profile-2018>{{cite web|title=Ava DuVernay Biography: Documentarian, Screenwriter, Director (1972\u2013)|url=https://www.biography.com/people/ava-duvernay|date=February 27, 2018|work=[[Biography (TV series)|Biography]]}}</ref><ref name=UCLAMag-MoN-2012>{{cite news|first1=Bekah|last1=Wright|title=Direct Actio|url=http://magazine.ucla.edu/depts/style/direct-action/|work=UCLA Magazine|publisher=[[University of California, Los Angeles]]|date=October 1, 2012}}</ref><ref name=TheCut-Conversation-2016>{{cite news|last1=Traister|first1=Rebecca|title=In Conversation: Ava DuVernay|url=https://www.thecut.com/2016/09/ava-duvernay-the-13th-queen-sugar-c-v-r.html|work=The Cut|publisher=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=September 19, 2016}}</ref><ref name=Agoralumiere-SaturdayNight-2006>{{cite web|last1=Miles|first1=Ellene V.|title=Agoralumiere Film Series: Saturday Night by Ava DuVernay (USA)|url=http://www.agoralumiere.org/FILMS/SATURDAY.htm|work=Agoralumiere at the Cannes Film Festival 2006|date=2006|format=Press release}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nDuVernay's first interest was in journalism, a choice influenced by an internship with [[CBS News]]. She was assigned to help cover the [[O.J. Simpson murder trial]].<ref name=UCLAMag-MoN-2012/> DuVernay became disillusioned with journalism, however, and decided to move into public relations, working as a junior publicist at [[20th Century Fox]], [[Savoy Pictures]], and a few other PR agencies. She opened her own public relations firm, The DuVernay Agency, also known as DVAPR, in 1999.<ref name=Vulture-Selma-Interview-2014>{{cite news|last1=Yuan|first1=Jada|title=With Her MLK Drama Selma, Ava DuVernay Is Directing History|url=https://www.vulture.com/2014/12/ava-duvernay-on-the-long-road-to-selma.html|work=[[Vulture.com|Vulture]]|date=2 December 2014|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThrough DVAPR she provided marketing and PR services to the entertainment and lifestyle industry, working on campaigns for movies and television shows, such as ''[[Lumumba (film)|Lumumba]]'', ''[[Spy Kids]]'', ''[[Shrek 2]]'', ''[[The Terminal]]'', ''[[Collateral (film)|Collateral]]'', and ''[[Dreamgirls (film)|Dreamgirls]]''.<ref name=Biography-Profile-2018 /><ref name=UCLAMag-MoN-2012 /><ref name=Agoralumiere-SaturdayNight-2006 /><ref name=CNN-MoN-2012>{{cite news|first1=Alicia W.|last1=Stewart|title=Filmmaker Ava DuVernay uses a lens of legacy|url=http://inamerica.blogs.cnn.com/2012/10/25/filmmaker-ava-duvernay-uses-a-lens-of-legacy/|work=[[CNN]]|date=October 25, 2012|format=Includes video and transcript}}</ref><ref name=NYTimes-MoN-2012>{{cite news|last1=Rickey|first1=Carrie|title=She's a Graduate of an Unusual Film School|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/07/movies/ava-duvernay-and-middle-of-nowhere.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 5, 2012}}</ref><ref name=Filmmaker-MoN-Interview-2012>{{cite news|first1=Nekisa|last1=Cooper|title=Love on the Outside|url=https://filmmakermagazine.com/57145-love-on-the-outside/|work=[[Filmmaker (magazine)|Filmmaker]]|date=November 1, 2012}}</ref><ref name=Source-Profile-2016>{{cite news|first1=Da'ryl|last1=Victoria|title=Breaking Barriers: Ava DuVernay Directs Things Her Way|url=http://thesource.com/2016/03/23/breaking-barriers-ava-duvernay-directs-things-her-way/|work=[[The Source]]|date=March 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOther ventures launched by DuVernay include Urban Beauty Collective, a promotional network that began in 2003 and had more than 10,000 African-American beauty salons and barbershops in 16 (20 since 2008) U.S. cities. They were mailed a free monthly ''[[Access Hollywood]]''-style promotion program called UBC-TV,<ref name=LATimes-UCBTV-2003>{{cite news|last1=Pollard-Terry|first1=Gayle|title=Style videos could start a new wave of good hair days|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2003/jul/05/entertainment/et-pollard5|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=July 5, 2003}}</ref><ref name=Billboard-UBCTV-2003>{{cite news|last1=Mitchell|first1=Gail|title=Firms Create Novel Marketing Twists|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0REEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA32|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=November 1, 2003}}</ref> the African-American blog hub Urban Thought Collective in 2008; Urban Eye, a two-minute long weekday celebrity and entertainment news show distributed to radio stations;<ref name=DVAHQ-2018>{{cite web|title=DVA Media + Marketing|url=http://www.dvahq.com/home.html|accessdate=February 4, 2018}}</ref> and [https://hellobeautiful.com/ HelloBeautiful], a digital platform for [[millennial]] [[women of color]].<ref name=InteractiveOne-HelloBeautiful-2013>{{cite news|title=HelloBeautiful.com Premieres Interludes Live! With Superstar John Legend On TV One Saturday Sep 14th @ 10 PM|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/hellobeautifulcom-premieres-interludes-live-with-superstar-john-legend-on-tv-one-saturday-sep-14th--10-pm-223670451.html|work=[[Interactive One]]|date=September 13, 2013|format=Press release}}</ref>\n\n===Film===\n[[File:DuVernaySanFranFilmFest.jpg|left|thumb|276x276px|DuVernay at the 2010 [[AFI Film Festival]]]]\nIn 2005, over the Christmas holiday, DuVernay decided to take $6,000 and make her first film, a short called ''Saturday Night Life''.<ref name=Agoralumiere-SaturdayNight-2006 /><ref name=Filmmaker-MoN-2012 /> Based on her mother's experiences,<ref name=Agoralumiere-SaturdayNight-2006 /> the 12-minute film was about an uplifting trip by a struggling single mother ([[Melissa De Sousa]]) and her three kids to a local Los Angeles discount grocery store. The film toured the festival circuit and was broadcast on February 6, 2007, as part of [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]'s ''Black Filmmaker Showcase''.<ref name=NewsBlaze-SaturdayNight-2009>{{cite news|first1=Kam|last1=Williams|title=Ava DuVernay 'This Is the Life' Interview with Kam Williams|url=https://newsblaze.com/entertainment/interviews/ava-duvernay-this-is-life-interview-with-kam-williams_8672/|work=NewsBlaze|date=March 17, 2009}}</ref>\n\nDuVernay next explored making documentaries, because they can be done on a smaller budget than fiction films, and she could learn the trade while doing so.<ref name=Interview-MoN-2012>{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Emma|title=In the Middle of Somewhere with Ava DuVernay and Emayatzy Corinealdi|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/film/ava-duvernay-emayatzy-corinealdi/|work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|date=October 11, 2012}}</ref> In 2007, she directed the short ''Compton in C Minor,'' for which she \"challenged herself to capture [[Compton, California|Compton]] in only two hours and present whatever she found.\" The following year, she made her feature directorial debut with the [[alternative hip hop]] documentary ''[[This Is the Life (2008 film)|This Is the Life]],'' a history of LA's [[Good Life Cafe]]'s arts movement, in which she participated as part of the duo [[Figures of Speech]].\n\nIn 2011, DuVernay's first narrative feature film, ''[[I Will Follow (film)|I Will Follow]]'', a drama starring [[Salli Richardson-Whitfield]], was released theatrically. DuVernay's aunt Denise Sexton was the inspiration for the film.<ref name=Filmmaker-MoN-2012>{{cite news|url=http://filmmakermagazine.com/37878-middle-of-nowhere-writer-director-ava-duvernay/|title=Middle of Nowhere \u2013 Writer/Director Ava DuVernay|work=[[Filmmaker (magazine)|Filmmaker]]|date=January 20, 2012}}</ref> The film cost DuVernay $50,000 and was made in 14 days.<ref name=NYTimes-MoN-2012 /> [[Roger Ebert]] called it \"one of the best films I've seen about coming to terms with the death of a loved one.\"<ref name=Ebert-IWF-Review-2012>{{cite news|last1=Ebert|first1=Roger|title=I Will Follow (2010). Genres: Drama. Roger's Office: I Will Follow|url=http://www.ebertpresents.com/movies/i-will-follow/videos/78|work=[[Ebert Presents: At the Movies]]|date=2012|format=Video includes transcript}}</ref><ref name=Ebert-IWF-Review-2011>{{cite news|last1=Ebert|first1=Roger|title=I Will Follow|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/i-will-follow-2011|work=[[RogerEbert.com]]|date=March 8, 2011}}</ref> ''I Will Follow'' was an official selection of [[AFI Fest]], [[Pan-African Film Festival]], Urbanworld and [[Chicago International Film Festival]].\n\nIn the summer of 2011, DuVernay began production on her second narrative feature film, ''[[Middle of Nowhere (2012 film)|Middle of Nowhere]]'', from a script she had written in 2003 but could not get financed then.<ref name=Filmmaker-MoN-2012 /> The film had its world premiere on January 20 at the [[2012 Sundance Film Festival]], where it played in U.S. dramatic competition.<ref name=HReporter-MoN-Sundance-2012>{{cite news|last1=Fernandez|first1=Jay A.|title=Sundance Preview: Competition Drama 'Middle of Nowhere'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/risky-business/sundance-preview-competition-drama-middle-280261|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=January 10, 2012|access-date=February 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204124118/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/risky-business/sundance-preview-competition-drama-middle-280261|archive-date=February 4, 2018|url-status = dead}}</ref> It garnered the U.S. Directing Award: Dramatic for DuVernay. She was the first African-American woman to win the prize. DuVernay also won the [[28th Independent Spirit Awards|2012]] [[Independent Spirit John Cassavetes Award]] for her work on the film.<ref name=Essence-MoN-ISAward-2013>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Celia L.|title=Ava DuVernay Wins Independent Spirit Award for 'Middle of Nowhere'|url=https://www.essence.com/2013/02/24/ava-duvernay-wins-independent-spirit-award-middle-nowhere|work=[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]|date=February 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nDuVernay was commissioned by the [[Smithsonian]]'s [[National Museum of African American History and Culture]] to create a film about [[African-American history]]. Her ''August 28: A Day in the Life of a People'' explores six significant events that happened on the same date, [[August 28]]; it debuted at the museum's opening on September 24, 2016. The 22-minute film stars [[Lupita Nyong'o]], [[Don Cheadle]], [[Regina King]], [[David Oyelowo]], [[Angela Bassett]], [[Michael Ealy]], [[Gugu Mbatha-Raw]], [[Andr\u00e9 Holland]] and [[Glynn Turman]]. Events depicted include [[William IV of the United Kingdom|William IV]]'s [[royal assent]] to the [[Slavery Abolition Act 1833|UK Slavery Abolition Act]] in 1833, the 1955 lynching of 14-year-old [[Emmett Till]] in [[Mississippi]], the release of [[Motown]]'s first number-one song, \"[[Please Mr. Postman]]\" by [[The Marvellettes]], Rev. Martin Luther King, Jr.'s 1963 ''[[I Have a Dream]]'' speech, the landfall of [[Hurricane Katrina]] in 2005, and the night Senator [[Barack Obama]] accepted the Democratic nomination for president at the [[2008 Democratic National Convention]].<ref name=Essence-NMAAHC-2016>{{cite news|last1=Davis|first1=Rachaell|title=Why Is August 28 So Special To Black People? Ava DuVernay Reveals All In New NMAAHC Film|url=http://www.essence.com/2016/09/22/ava-duvernay-premiere-nmaahc|work=[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]|date=September 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====''Selma''====\n{{Main|Selma (film)}}\nDuVernay directed ''[[Selma (film)|Selma]]'', a $20 million budget dramatic film produced by [[Plan B Entertainment]], about the Rev. [[Martin Luther King, Jr.]], President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]], and the [[Selma to Montgomery marches|1965 Selma to Montgomery march]] for voting rights.<ref name=Indiewire-Selma-2013>{{cite news|last1=Obenson|first1=Tambay|title=Huge! Ava DuVernay Tapped By Brad Pitt's Plan B To Take Over Lee Daniels' 'Selma'|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/shadowandact/huge-ava-duvernay-tapped-by-brad-pitts-plan-b-to-take-over-lee-daniels-selma|work=[[IndieWire]]|date=July 11, 2013}}</ref> The movie was released on December 25, 2014 to critical acclaim.<ref name=Indiewire-Selma-2014>{{cite news|first1=Kevin|last1=Jagernauth|title=Ava DuVernay's 'Selma' Enters Oscar Race, Sets Christmas Day Release|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/ava-duvernays-selma-enters-oscar-race-sets-christmas-day-release-20140620|work=[[IndieWire]]|date=June 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\nShe made uncredited re-writes of most of the original screenplay by Paul Webb in order to emphasize King and the people of Selma as central figures.<ref name=WashPost-Selma-2014>{{cite news|last1=Hornaday|first1=Ann|title=DuVernay, David Oyelowo on breaking Martin Luther King Jr. out of myth and into life|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/ava-duvernay-david-oyelowo-on-breaking-martin-luther-king-jr-out-of-myth-and-into-life/2014/12/25/0caceefc-8b71-11e4-a085-34e9b9f09a58_story.html|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=December 26, 2014}}</ref><ref name=NewYorker-Selma-2014>{{cite news|last1=Brody|first1=Richard|title=The Crucial Lessons of Democracy in \"Selma\"|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/richard-brody/crucial-lessons-democracy-selma|work=[[The New Yorker]]|date=December 29, 2014}}</ref> In response to criticism by some historians and media sources who accused her of irresponsibly rewriting history to portray her own agenda, DuVernay said that the film is \"not a documentary. I'm not a historian. I'm a storyteller\".<ref name=Reuters-Selma-2015>{{cite news|last1=Milliken|first1=Mary|title='Selma' director makes history before awards are bestowed|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/01/06/film-selma-duvernay-idUSL1N0UK2C920150106|work=[[Reuters]]|date=January 6, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe film was nominated for [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] and [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]], but not [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]], at the 2014 [[Academy Awards]]. The lack of diversity among the Oscar nominations for 2014 was the subject of much press,<ref name=Grantland-Selma-2015>{{cite news|last1=Harris|first1=Mark|title=How 'Selma' Got Smeared: On historical drama and its malcontents|url=http://grantland.com/features/selma-oscars-academy-awards-historical-accuracy-controversy/|work=[[Grantland]]|date=January 28, 2015}}</ref> especially on [[Twitter]].<ref name=DemocracyNow-OscarSnub-2015>{{cite news|last1=Goodman|first1=Amy|last2=DuVernay|first2=Ava|title=Selma Director Ava DuVernay on Hollywood's Lack of Diversity, Oscar Snub and #OscarsSoWhite Hashtag|url=https://www.democracynow.org/2015/1/27/selma_director_ava_duvernay_on_hollywoods|work=[[Democracy Now!]]|date=January 27, 2015|format=Video interview includes transcript}}</ref> This film was the only one directed by a [[person of color]] that was nominated for the [[87th Academy Awards]]. The award for [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] went to \"[[Glory (Common and John Legend song)|Glory]]\" from ''Selma''.<ref name=ABCNews-Oscars-2015>{{cite news|title=List of 87th Academy Award Winners|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory/partial-list-oscar-winners-29149735|agency=[[Associated Press]]|work=[[ABC News]]|date=February 23, 2015}}</ref><ref name=LatinPost-Oscars-2015>{{cite news|last1=Ontiveros|first1=Roberto|title=Oscars 2015: A Look at Biggest Latino Oscar Winners of the Past|url=https://www.latinpost.com/articles/39035/20150222/http-admin-latinpost-com-pages-publish-publish-form-php-se-mb-no-138-getstring-se-mb-no-3d138-26amp-3b.htm|work=LatinPost|date=February 22, 2015}}</ref> DuVernay said that she had not expected to be nominated as director, so the omission did not really bother her; but she was disappointed that actor [[David Oyelowo]], who portrayed King, was not nominated as Best Actor. She said that the obstacles to people of color being represented in the Academy Awards were systemic.<ref name=DemocracyNow-OscarSnub-2015 />\n[[File:Ava DuVernay - Peabody Awards (cropped).jpg|thumb|289x289px|Duvernay with her [[Peabody Award]] for ''[[13th (film)|13th]]'' at the 76th annual ceremony in 2017]]\n\n====''13th''====\n{{Main|13th (film)}}\nIn July 2016, the [[New York Film Festival]] made the surprise announcement that ''[[13th (film)|13th]]'', a documentary directed by DuVernay, would open the festival. Until the announcement no mention of the film had been made by either DuVernay or [[Netflix]], the film's distributor.<ref name=Variety-NYFF-13th-2016>{{cite news|last1=Cox|first1=Gordon|title=2016 New York Film Festival to Open With Ava DuVernay Documentary 'The 13th'|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/new-york-film-festival-2016-opening-night-1201817239/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=July 19, 2016}}</ref> Centered on [[race in the United States criminal justice system]], the film is titled after the [[Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]], which outlawed slavery (unless as punishment for a crime). DuVernay's documentary opens with the statement that 25 percent of the people in the world who are incarcerated are incarcerated in the U.S., and argues that slavery has been effectively perpetuated in the U.S. through disproportionate [[mass incarceration]] of people of color. The film features several prominent activists, politicians, and public figures, such as [[Bryan Stevenson]], [[Angela Davis]], [[Van Jones]], [[Newt Gingrich]], [[Cory Booker]], [[Henry Louis Gates Jr.]], and others, who discuss such issues as convict leasing, the war on drugs, and disproportionate arrests, convictions and sentencing of minorities.<ref name=Guardian-13th-2016>{{cite news|last1=Smith|first1=Nigel M.|title=The 13th: inside Ava DuVernay's Netflix prison documentary on racial inequality|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/sep/26/the-13th-trailer-ava-duvernay-netflix-prison-race|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=September 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIt was released on October 7, 2016 on [[Netflix]].<ref name=Vulture-NYFF-2016>{{cite news|last1=Lockett|first1=Dee|title=Ava DuVernay's The 13th Will Be the First Documentary to Ever Open the New York Film Festival|url=https://www.vulture.com/2016/07/ava-duvernay-documentary-the-13th-to-open-nyff.html|work=[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]]|date=19 July 2016}}</ref> ''13th'' garnered acclaim from film critics and has a 97% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 94 reviews. The critical consensus says: \"''13th'' strikes at the heart of America's tangled racial history, offering observations as incendiary as they are calmly controlled.\"<ref name=RottenTomatoes-13th-2916>{{cite web|title=13th (2016)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/13th|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|access-date=September 30, 2016}}</ref> In a review from Awards Circuit, Angela Davis said \"''13th'' is probably the most important movie you'll ever see.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.avaduvernay.com/|title=Ava DuVernay|website=Ava DuVernay|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-30}}</ref> In 2017, the film was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature]] at the [[89th Academy Awards|89th Oscars]];<ref name=AMPAS-OscarNoms-2017>{{cite web|title=Oscar Nominations|url=http://oscar.go.com/nominees|work=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]|access-date=January 24, 2017}}</ref> DuVernay became the first black woman to be nominated by the academy as a director in a feature category.<ref name=Vogue-OscarNoms-2017>{{cite news|first1=Patricia|last1=Garcia|title=Ava DuVernay Doesn't Want Praise, She Wants Change|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/ava-duvernay-oscar-nomination-oscars-so-male|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]|date=February 6, 2017}}</ref> The film also won a [[Peabody Award]] in 2017<ref name=HReporter-PeabodyAwards-13th-2017>{{cite news|last1=Nordyke|first1=Kimberly|last2=Lewis|first2=Hilary|title=Peabody Awards: Norman Lear, 'Lemonade,' 'Atlanta,' 'Veep' Among Winners|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/peabody-awards-oj-made-america-13th-documentary-winners-995048|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=18 April 2017|language=en}}</ref> and a [[Columbia Journalism School]] [[Dupont Award|duPont Award]] in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://journalism.columbia.edu/winners-2018-dupont-columbia-awards|title=Winners of the 2018 duPont-Columbia Awards|last=|first=|date=|website=Columbia University in the City of New York|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n====''A Wrinkle in Time''====\n{{Main|A Wrinkle in Time (2018 film)}}\nIn 2010, it was announced that [[Disney]] carried the [[A Wrinkle in Time (2018 film)|film rights]] to the 1962 novel ''[[A Wrinkle in Time]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://screenrant.com/a-wrinkle-in-time-film-disne-benk-49886/|title=Script in the Works for 'A Wrinkle in Time'|work=[[Screen Rant]]|last=Kendrick|first=Ben|date=March 23, 2010}}</ref> Following the success of [[Tim Burton]]'s ''[[Alice in Wonderland (2010 film)|Alice in Wonderland]]'', Disney announced the hire of Jeff Stockwell to write the screenplay for [[Cary Granat]] and his new [[Bedrock Studios]]. Cary Granat had previously worked with Disney on the ''[[The Chronicles of Narnia (film series)|Chronicles of Narnia]]'' and ''[[Bridge to Terabithia (2007 film)|Bridge to Terabithia]]'' films.<ref name=HReporter-Wrinkle-Stockwell-2010>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bedrock-taps-jeff-stockwell-adapt-21791|title=Bedrock taps Jeff Stockwell to adapt 'Wrinkle'|last=Fernandez|first=Jay|date=October 14, 2010|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref> On August 5, 2014, [[Jennifer Lee (filmmaker)|Jennifer Lee]] was announced as the screenwriter, taking over from Stockwell, who had written the first draft.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/frozen-director-jennifer-lee-to-adapt-a-wrinkle-in-time-for-disney-exclusive-1201275488/|title='Frozen' Director Jennifer Lee to Adapt 'A Wrinkle in Time' for Disney|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=August 5, 2014|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref><ref name=SlashFilm-Wrinkle-2014>{{cite news|last1=Han|first1=Angie|title='Frozen' Director Jennifer Lee to Adapt 'A Wrinkle in Time'|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/a-wrinkle-in-time-movie-jennifer-lee/|work=Slash Film|date=August 5, 2014}}</ref> On February 8, 2016, it was reported that DuVernay had been offered to direct the film, and she was confirmed as director later that same month.<ref name=Feb2016THR>{{cite news|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title=Lupita Nyong'o in Talks to Star in Sci-Fi Thriller With Ava DuVernay Eyed to Direct (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/lupita-nyongo-talks-star-sci-863100|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=February 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n''[[A Wrinkle in Time (2018 film)|A Wrinkle in Time]]'' began filming in November 2016. DuVernay is the first woman of color to direct a live-action film with a budget of over $100 million, and the second woman to do so after [[Patty Jenkins]] (who directed ''[[Wonder Woman (2017 film)|Wonder Woman]]'').<ref name=LATimes-WrinkleBudget-2016 />\n\nThe film was released in March 2018 and brought in $33 million its opening weekend, second at the box office behind ''[[Black Panther (film)|Black Panther]].''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/12/entertainment/wrinkle-time-black-panther-trnd/index.html|title=This weekend was the first time films by black directors with mega budgets held the top 2 spots at the box office|first=Lisa Respers |last=France|work=[[CNN]]|date=12 March 2018}}</ref> Following Disney's Q2 earnings report in May 2018, [[Yahoo! Finance]] deduced the film would lose the studio anywhere from $86\u2013186 million.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/lone-loser-disneys-big-quarter-wrinkle-time-220638977.html|title=The lone loser in Disney's big quarter: 'A Wrinkle in Time'|work=[[Yahoo! Finance]]|date=May 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nUpon release, the film received mixed reviews, with critics \"taking issue with the film's heavy use of [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] and numerous plot holes\" while \"celebrating its message of female empowerment and diversity.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/wrinkle-in-time-reviews-roundup-critic-response-1202720742/|title='A Wrinkle in Time' Reviews: What the Critics Are Saying|author=Kirsten Chuba|date=March 7, 2018|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n===Television===\nIn 2010, DuVernay directed three TV documentaries. The first, two-hour concert film ''TV One Night Only: Live from the Essence Music Festival'', was a mix of live performances and behind-the-scenes vignettes. It aired August 28, 2010 on [[TV One (U.S. TV network)|TV One]] and showcases the U.S.'s largest annual African-American entertainment gathering, the [[Essence Music Festival]]. In 2010 it was held July 2\u20134 in [[New Orleans]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.philasun.com/entertainment/tv-one-features-specials-of-the-2010-essence-music-festival-washington-watch-and-life-after-aug-29-30/|title=TV One features specials of the 2010 Essence Music Festival, Washington Watch and Life After, Aug. 29-30|work=The Philadelphia Sunday Sun|date=August 29, 2010}}</ref> Two days later, [[BET]] premiered its first original music documentary, ''My Mic Sounds Nice: A Truth About Women and Hip Hop'', a 41-minute long history of female hip hop artists.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=129530573|title=Female Emcees Say 'My Mic Sounds Nice'|work=[[NPR]]|date=August 30, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn [[Thanksgiving (United States)|Thanksgiving]] 2010, TV One showed DuVernay's 44-minute documentary special ''Essence Presents: Faith Through the Storm'', about two black sisters who reclaimed their lives after personal devastation during Hurricane Katrina. \"It was done for a client, for ''[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]''. They wanted to talk about how faith helped them through, that was very important to them. So it is interspersed with gospel music, images of Katrina, their home and family.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.intrepidmedia.com/column.asp?id=4201|title=An Interview with Ava DuVernay|work=Intrepid Media|first=Jason|last=Gilmore|date=November 12, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[ESPN]] commissioned DuVernay to produce and direct ''Venus Vs.'', a documentary on [[Venus Williams]]'s fight for equal prize money. This was to be included in their film series ''[[Nine for IX]]'', which aired on July 2, 2013.<ref name=ESPN-IX-2013>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/espnw/nine-for-ix/8948839/nine-ix-film-summary-director-venus-vs|title=Nine for IX: 'Venus Vs.'|work=[[ESPN]]|date=June 26, 2013|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527074437/http://espn.go.com/espnw/nine-for-ix/8948839/nine-ix-film-summary-director-venus-vs|archivedate=May 27, 2013}}</ref> \n\nDuVernay also directed the [[John Legend]] episode of the performance-and-interview series ''HelloBeautiful Interludes Live'', which was shown September 14, 2013 on TV One as the series' broadcast premiere.<ref name=InteractiveOne-HelloBeautiful-2013 /> She also directed the eighth episode of the third season of the [[political thriller]] [[television series]] ''[[Scandal (TV series)|Scandal]]''. The episode, titled \"[[Vermont is For Lovers, Too|Vermont is for Lovers, Too]]\", premiered on November 21, 2013 on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]].<ref name=Indiewire-Scandal-2013>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/shadowandact/ava-duvernay-will-direct-an-episode-of-scandal-next-season|title=Ava DuVernay Will Direct An Episode Of 'Scandal' Next Season|work=[[IndieWire]]|date=July 12, 2013|first=Tambay A.|last=Obenson}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, DuVernay executive produced and directed the [[CBS]] civil rights crime drama pilot ''For Justice'', starring [[Anika Noni Rose]].<ref name=HReporter-ForJustice-2015>{{cite news|last1=Goldberg|first1=Lesley|title='Selma's' Ava DuVernay 'For Justice'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/selmas-ava-duvernay-justice-772276|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 10, 2015}}</ref> It was not picked up for distribution.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}} \n\nThat same year, DuVernay announced she would be creating and executive producing the drama series ''[[Queen Sugar]]'', based on Natalie Baszile's [[Queen Sugar (novel)|novel]].<ref name=Deadline-QueenSugar-2015>{{cite news|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|title=Oprah Winfrey To Co-Star In & Co-Create With 'Selma' Filmmaker Ava DuVernay 'Queen Sugar' OWN Drama Series|url=https://deadline.com/2015/02/oprah-winfrey-selma-filmmaker-ava-duvernay-queen-sugar-own-drama-series-1201364863/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=February 2, 2015}}</ref><ref name=HReporter-QueenSugar-Oprah-2015>{{cite news|last1=Wilson|first1=Stacey|title='Selma' Director Ava DuVernay on 'Awkward and Weird' First Meeting With Oprah Winfrey|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/selma-director-ava-duvernay-awkward-774627|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=February 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''Queen Sugar'' premiered September 6, 2016 on [[Oprah Winfrey Network (U.S. TV channel)|Oprah Winfrey Network]] to critical acclaim and positive reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/queen_sugar/|title=Queen Sugar (2016 - 2017)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|access-date=September 30, 2016}}</ref> DuVernay wrote four episodes and directed two. On August 1, 2016, the series was renewed for a second season ahead of its television premiere; it aired in a two-night premiere on June 20 and June 21, 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2016/08/oprah-winfrey-ava-duvernay-queen-sugar-gets-season-2-renewal-own-1201796851/|title=Ava DuVernay-Directed 'Queen Sugar' Gets Season 2 Pickup From OWN \u2013 TCA|last=Patten|first=Dominic|date=August 1, 2016|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://shadowandact.com/2016/08/01/own-renews-queen-sugar-for-a-16-episode-second-season-ahead-of-its-season-1-premiere/|title=OWN Gives 'Queen Sugar' an Early 16-Episode Second Season Renewal + A New Trailer|date=August 1, 2016|work=[[Shadow and Act]]}}</ref> The series was renewed for a third season on July 26, 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/more-tv-news/queen-sugar-scores-season-3-renewal-on-own/|title='Queen Sugar' scores Season 3 renewal on OWN|last=Porter|first=Rick|date=July 26, 2017|work=[[TV by the Numbers]]}}</ref> In August 2018, OWN renewed the series for a fourth season, which premiered on June 12, 2019. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/queen-sugar-renewed-season-4-own-new-showrunner-anthony-sparks-1202442491/</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/tv-news-roundup-tiffany-haddish-ali-wong-netflix-animated-comedy-1203163416//</ref> \n\nOn July 6, 2017, it was announced that [[Netflix]] had given the production ''[[When They See Us]]'' a series order consisting of four episodes. The series was created by DuVernay, who served as executive producer, co-writer, and director. Other executive producers credited, include [[Jeff Skoll]], [[Jonathan King]], [[Oprah Winfrey]], [[Jane Rosenthal]] and Berry Welsh. Production companies involved with the series consisted of [[Participant Media]], [[Harpo Films]], and [[Tribeca Productions]].<ref name=\"WhenTheySeeUsNetflixOrder\">{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|title=Ava DuVernay Teaming With Netflix On Central Park Five Limited Drama Series|url=https://deadline.com/2017/07/ava-duvernay-netflix-on-central-park-five-limited-drama-series-1202124535/|website=Deadline Hollywood|access-date=May 31, 2019|date=July 6, 2017}}</ref> The series premiered on Netflix on May 31, 2019. Upon its release, the miniseries received critical universal acclaim.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/tv-movies/a26588461/when-they-see-us-netflix-central-park-five-series-ava-duvernay/|title=Ava DuVernay's \"When They See Us\" Looks at the Central Park Five\u2014Here's What to Know|last=Darrisaw|first=Michelle|work=The Oprah Magazine|date=May 14, 2019|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/reviews/ava-duvernay-when-they-see-us-1203220510/|title=TV Review: Ava DuVernay's 'When They See Us'|last=D'Addario|first=Daniel|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=May 21, 2019|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/when-they-see-us-2019|title=When They See Us Review|last=Henderson|first=Odie|work=[[Roger Ebert]]|date=May 30, 2019|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/they-see-us-review-1211524|title='When They See Us': TV Review|last=Fienberg|first=Daniel|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=May 31, 2019|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/when-they-see-us-review-netflix/|title='When They See Us' Review: Ava DuVernay's Magnum Opus of a Broken America|last=Goldberg|first=Matt|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|date=May 31, 2019|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/may/31/when-they-see-us-review-netflix-ava-duvernay-central-park-five|title=When They See Us review \u2013 Netflix's gut-wrenching tale of the Central Park Five|last=Mangan|first=Lucy|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=May 31, 2019|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/05/when-they-see-us-netflix-review.html|title=When They See Us Is an Intimate, Sensitive Look at the Central Park Five Tragedy|last=Chaney|first=Jen|work=Vulture|date=May 30, 2019|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://slate.com/culture/2019/05/when-they-see-us-central-park-five-netflix-review.html|title=When They See Us Is a New Kind of Must-See TV|last=Paskin|first=Willa|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=May 30, 2019|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-when-they-see-us-review-netflix-duvernay-20190529-story.html|title=Review: Ava DuVernay's 'When They See Us' gets to the human heart of the Central Park Five|last=Lloyd|first=Robert|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=May 30, 2019|access-date=May 31, 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn June 25, 2019, Netflix announced that the miniseries had been streamed by over 23 million viewers within its first month of release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/when-they-see-us-watched-by-more-than-23-million-netflix-accounts-worldwide-1202638036/|title='When They See Us' Watched By More Than 23 Million Netflix Accounts Worldwide|last=Bennett|first=Anita|work=Deadline Hollywood|access-date=June 25, 2019|date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> It has received a record number of 16 nominations for Emmy Awards for writing, directing, and acting for stars and supporting actors.\n\n===Advertising and music videos===\nIn 2013, DuVernay partnered with [[Miu Miu]] as part of their ''[[Women's Tales]]'' film series.<ref name=MiuMiu-Door-2014>{{cite web|title=\"The Door\" by Ava DuVernay: Women's Tales #5|url=http://www.miumiu.com/en/women_tales/5/film|work=[[Miu Miu]]|date=2014}}</ref> Her short film ''The Door'' starred actress [[Gabrielle Union]] and reunited DuVernay with her ''[[Middle of Nowhere (2012 film)|Middle of Nowhere]]'' star [[Emayatzy Corinealdi]]. The film premiered online in February 2013<ref name=Interview-Door-2013>{{cite news|last1=Small|first1=Rachel|title=Ava DuVernay Brings Us Through the Door|url=http://www.interviewmagazine.com/fashion/ava-duvernay-brings-us-through-the-door|work=[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]|date=February 11, 2013}}</ref> and was presented at the ''Venice Days'' sidebar of the [[70th Venice International Film Festival]] in August.<ref name=HuffPo-Door-2013>{{cite news|last1=Rothe|first1=E. Nina|title=Best of Venice 70: 'Miu Miu Women's Tales' \u2013 The Door and Le Donne della Vucciri|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/e-nina-rothe/best-of-venice-70-miu-miu_b_3842140.html|work=[[Huffington Post]]|date=August 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAlso in August 2013, DuVernay released, through [[Vimeo]],<ref name=SayYes-2013>{{Vimeo|71992175|DuVernay <nowiki>|</nowiki> Say Yes}}, uploaded August 8, 2013.</ref> a second branded short film entitled ''Say Yes''.<ref name=Ebony-SayYes-2013>{{cite news|title=Fashion Fair presents Say Yes by Ava DuVernay|url=http://www.ebony.com/style/fashion-fair-presents-say-yes-by-ava-duvernay-987|work=[[Ebony (magazine)|Ebony]]|date=August 16, 2013}}</ref> The film was sponsored by cosmetic brand [[Ebony Fashion Fair|Fashion Fair]] and starred [[Kali Hawk]] and [[Lance Gross]] with [[Julie Dash]], [[Victoria Mahoney]], [[Lorraine Toussaint]] and [[Issa Rae]] appearing as extras.\n\nIn 2015, [[Apple Music]] and their ad agency Translation hired DuVernay to helm a series of three commercials starring [[Mary J. Blige]], [[Taraji P. Henson]] and [[Kerry Washington]]. The first ad, ''Chapter 1'', premiered during [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]'s [[67th Primetime Emmy Awards|Emmy broadcast]] on September 20, 2015.<ref name=AdAge-EmmysAppleAd-2015>{{cite news|last1=Diaz|first1=Ann-Christine|title=How Apple Music's Star-Studded Emmys Ad Came Together|url=http://adage.com/article/advertising/apple-s-star-studded-emmy-s-ad/300463/|work=[[AdAge]]|date=September 21, 2015}}</ref> ''Chapter 2'' and ''Chapter 3'' debuted in November 2015 and February 2016, respectively.<ref name=CreativityOnline-2018>{{cite news|title=Ava DuVernay|url=http://creativity-online.com/credits/ava-duvernay/77188/1|work=[[Creativity (magazine)|Creativity]]|publisher=[[AdAge]]|date=2018}}</ref>\n\nHer music video for the [[Jay-Z]] ft. [[Beyonc\u00e9]] song \"[[4:44 (album)#Music videos|Family Feud]]\" premiered December 29, 2017 on [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref name=VanityFair-FamilyFeud-2017>{{cite news|last1=Stefansky|first1=Emma|title=Jay-Z Confesses His Sins to Beyonc\u00e9 in Ava DuVernay-Directed \"Family Feud\" Music Video|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2017/12/jay-z-ava-duvernay-family-feud-music-video|work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Film distribution and production===\n{{main|ARRAY}}\nIn 2010 DuVernay founded African-American Film Festival Releasing Movement ([[AFFRM]]), her own company to distribute films made by or focusing on black people. DuVernay refers to AFFRM as \"not so much a business, but a call to action.\"<ref name=NYTimes-AFFRM-2011>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/08/movies/08urban.html|title=Building an Alliance to Aid Films by Blacks|date=January 7, 2011|work=[[The New York Times]]|last=Cieply|first=Michael}}</ref> Although she sees building strong business foundations for films is a priority, DuVernay has said that she stresses that the driving force of the organization is activism.<ref name=:0 /> In 2015 the company rebranded itself under the name [[ARRAY]], promising a new focus on women filmmakers as well.\n\nDuVernay also owns Forward Movement, a film and television production company.<ref name=:0>{{Cite journal|last=Martin|first=Michael T.|date=Fall 2014|title=Conversations with Ava DuVernay\u2014\"A Call to Action\": Organizing Principles of an Activist Cinematic Practice|journal=Black Camera|volume=6|issue=1|pages=57\u201391|doi=10.2979/blackcamera.6.1.57}}</ref>\n\n===Future projects===\nIn 2013, she announced development on a narrative feature film entitled ''Part of the Sky'' and set in Compton.<ref>{{cite web|work=Strutta|url=http://affinity.strutta.com/entry/1205618|title=Ava DuVernay <nowiki>|</nowiki> Heineken Affinity Award|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030220033/http://affinity.strutta.com/entry/1205618|archivedate=October 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, it was announced that DuVernay would be writing, producing, and directing a fictional account which will focus on the \"social and environmental\" aspects of Hurricane Katrina while including a love story and a murder mystery.<ref name=WashPost-Katrina-2015>{{cite news|last=Rosenberg|first=Alyssa|title='Selma' criticism isn't stopping Ava DuVernay|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/act-four/wp/2015/01/26/selma-criticism-cant-stop-ava-duvernay/|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=January 26, 2015}}</ref> [[David Oyelowo]] was said to be part of the project.<ref name=LATimes-Katrina-2015>{{cite news|last=Gettell|first=Oliver|title=Ava DuVernay, David Oyelowo to reunite on Hurricane Katrina drama|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-ava-duvernay-david-oyelowo-hurricane-katrina-drama-20150126-story.html|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, it was announced that DuVernay would be directing a [[New Gods]] film for the [[DC Extended Universe]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Ava DuVernay to Direct DC's Superhero Epic 'New Gods'|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/ava-duvernay-superhero-movie-new-gods-dc-1202725043/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 16, 2018}}</ref>  On May 29, 2019, DuVernay announced that she and [[Tom King (writer)|Tom King]] will co-write the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2019/05/29/tom-king-new-gods-script-ava-duvernay/|title=Batman writer Tom King teams up with Ava DuVernay for New Gods script|last=Agard|first=Chancellor|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|date=May 29, 2019|accessdate=May 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn October 29, 2018, it was announced that DuVernay would be working with the estate of [[Prince (musician)|Prince]] to direct a biopic covering his entire life for Netflix.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/oct/30/ava-duvernay-prince-documentary-netflix|title=Ava DuVernay to make Prince documentary for Netflix|last=Beaumont-Thomas|first=Ben|date=2018-10-30|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-05-29|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>  However, in August 2019, it was announced that DuVernay quit as director due to \"creative differences.\" <ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.startribune.com/ava-duvernay-quits-as-director-of-netflix-s-authorized-prince-documentary/557885482/ | title=Ava DuVernay quits as director of Netflix's authorized Prince documentary}}</ref>\n\nOn February 11, 2020, news reports came out about Ava DuVernay possibly co-producing and directing a [[Nipsey Hussle]] documentary or [[Netflix]] series. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/nipsey-hussle-documentary-netflix-ava-duvernay-1203500697/|title=Nipsey Hussle Documentary From Ava DuVernay in Preliminary Stages at Netflix|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=February 11, 2020|accessdate=February 13, 2020|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref>\n\n===Other work===\nIn September 2013, DuVernay started a podcast series called ''The Call-In,''<ref name=Filmmaker-Podcast-2013>{{cite news|last=Macaulay|first=Scott|title=Ava DuVernay and AFFRM Launch Podcast, 'The Call In,' with Andrew Dosumnu|url=http://filmmakermagazine.com/76243-ava-duvernay-and-affrm-launch-podcast-the-call-in-with-andrew-dosumnu/|work=[[Filmmaker (magazine)|Filmmaker]]|date=September 19, 2013}}</ref> a series of phone conversations recorded by AFFRM of Black filmmakers of feature narrative and documentary work.\n\nDuVernay, in a keynote address<ref name=Variety-SXSWKeynote-2015>{{cite news|last=Setoodeh|first=Ramin|title='Selma's' Ava DuVernay: 'Studios Aren't Lining Up for Black Protagonists'|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/selmas-ava-duvernay-studios-arent-lining-up-for-black-protagonists-1201452855/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 14, 2015}}</ref> at the 2015 [[SXSW Film Festival]],<ref name=SXSW-FilmKeynote-Schedule-2015>{{cite news|title=Ava DuVernay Keynote|url=http://schedule.sxsw.com/2015/events/event_FP991057|work=[[SXSW]]|date=March 2015}}</ref><ref name=IndieWire-SXSWKeynote-2015>{{cite news|last=Obenson|first=Tambay A.|title=Watch Ava DuVernay's Rousing SXSW Keynote Address|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/shadowandact/watch-ava-duvernays-rousing-sxsw-keynote-address-20150317|work=[[IndieWire]]|date=March 17, 2015}}</ref> shared that she was the seventh choice of people asked to direct ''Selma''<ref name=IndieWire-SXSW-7Things-2015>{{cite news|last=Canfield|first=David|title=SXSW: The 7 Best Things We Learned From Ava DuVernay's Keynote Speech|url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/sxsw-the-7-best-things-we-learned-from-ava-duvernays-keynote-speech-20150318|work=[[IndieWire]]|date=March 18, 2015}}</ref> and described her experience at the [[87th Academy Awards|2015 Oscars]], while being an honor to be able to attend, it was just \"a room in L.A.\"<ref name=HReporter-SXSW-Oscars-2015>{{cite news|last=Abramovitch|first=Seth|title=SXSW: Ava DuVernay Calls Oscars a \"Room in L.A.\" at Rousing Keynote|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sxsw-ana-duvernay-calls-oscars-781521|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018 it was announced that DuVernay, along with producer [[Dan Lin]] and Los Angeles Mayor [[Eric Garcetti]], had launched the Evolve Entertainment Fund. The fund's mission is to promote inclusion and provide an opportunity for under-served communities to pursue a dream in the entertainment industry.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Ava DuVernay, Dan Lin, Los Angeles Mayor Eric Garcetti Launch Inclusion Fund|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/ava-duvernay-dan-lin-eric-garcetti-inclusion-1202695182/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=12 February 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nSince May 2019, DuVernay has cohosted ''[[The Essentials (TCM)|The Essentials]]'', a weekly film series on [[Turner Classic Movies]], with [[Ben Mankiewicz]]. DuVernay has appeared in [[Interstitial program|wraparounds]] each Saturday night on the channel, discussing a wide range of films, including ''[[Marty (film)|Marty]]'', ''[[Ashes and Embers]]'', ''[[Harlan County, USA]]'' and ''[[La Pointe Courte]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/ava-duvernay-joins-tcm-discuss-essentials-1204680|title=Ava DuVernay Joins TCM to Discuss 'The Essentials'|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>\n\n==Style and themes==\nMichael T. Martin says, \"DuVernay is among the vanguard of a new generation of black filmmakers who are the busily undeterred catalyst for what may very well be a black film renaissance in the making.\"<ref name=:0 /> He further speaks of DuVernay's mission and \"call to action\" which constitutes a strategy \"to further and foster the black cinematic image in an organized and consistent way, and to not have to defer and ask permission to traffic our films: to be self-determining.\"<ref name=:0 />\n\n==Personal life==\nDuVernay is private about her romantic life. She has been linked to rapper [[Common (rapper)|Common]], who starred in and wrote music for the 2014 film she directed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://liverampup.com/entertainment/director-ava-duvernay-does-have-boyfriend-secretly-married-husband.html|title=Director Ava DuVernay: Does She Have a Boyfriend? Or is She Secretly Married? Husband?|date=2016-09-27|website=LIVERAMPUP|language=en|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{|